It is not possible from know which node is connected to which from code.
I.e. you can't know which animation is played by this particular blend2 node, for example.
This way if you want to do soma automation, like clean-up animations which are attached to
blending nodes saving animators work and frees yourself from editing messy filters,
you have to guess, which is not good.
You can do the following:

``` gdscript
var anim_filters = {}
func _ready():
    var nodes = Array(get_node_list())
    for m in nodes:
        print(m)
        var t = node_get_type(m)
        if t == NODE_ANIMATION:
            var anm = animation_node_get_animation(m)
            if anm == null:
                var pl = get_master_player()
                var pln = get_node(pl)
                var anim = animation_node_get_master_animation(m)
                anm = pln.get_animation(anim)
            anim_filters[anm.get_name()] = []
            for l in range(anm.get_track_count()):
                var track_type = anm.track_get_type(l)
                if anm.track_get_key_count(l) == 2:
                    anim_filters[anm.get_name()].append(anm.track_get_path(l))
    for m in nodes:
        var t = node_get_type(m)
        if t == NODE_ONESHOT:
            for np in anim_filters[m]:
                oneshot_node_set_filter_path(m, np, true)
```

... etc.
for simple cases which will fill filters for each animation,
then use that filter for matching nodes (named the same as animation)
but this is ugly and stupid.
You should be able to know at _ready time whet is your ATP node setup,
which allows to do small tricks like this without ugly hacks.

Tested on Windows. Mac & Linux possibly have this issue as well.

The game window (along with the splash screen window) on the Desktop platforms should be centered on game start for better UX+presentation. Currently I have to write a script to do that:

```gdscript
func _ready():

    var windowSize = Vector2(1280, 720);

    OS.set_window_resizable(false);
    OS.set_window_fullscreen(false);
    OS.set_window_size(windowSize);

    var displaySize = OS.get_screen_size();

    var windowX = (displaySize.width - windowSize.width)/2;
    var windowY = (displaySize.height - windowSize.height)/2;

    OS.set_window_position(Vector2(windowX, windowY));
```

_Using Godot 2.0.2_
